2 Data

phen <- copdgene_phen(traits = "main", acs = "acs_global", progress = FALSE) 
phen <- subset(phen, !is.na(acs_global))
annot <- copdgene_annot_acs()
annot <- mutate(annot,
  length = pos_end - pos_start,
  pos_mid = (pos_start + pos_end) / 2,
  long = ifelse(length > 10e3, ">10kb", ""))

2.1 Combination of smoking variables

Michael: Alternative modeling to that about SmokCigNow + Packs_Year

  • Duration_Smoking + CigPerDaySmokAvg = Packs_Year
  • CigPerDaySmokNow (cont.) = SmokCigNow (binary)

Idea: exploit all available variables to describe the smoking behavior:

  • Use as many smoking variables as possible
  • Train a machine learning model such as a decision tree
    • robust to missing data
    • produces latent grouping variables (6 boxes at the bottom of the next figure)
  • Use output groups as a factor variable with many levels
    • Another random effect?
    • A fixed effect variables with many levels?
      • Use a method for many exposures that Jihye is currently developing
    • (todo) Use the standard measures (error in prediction, etc) to prove the proposed model is better than just linear regression with SmokCigNow + Packs_Year
  • Do output groups have any sense for MDs? (Michaels feedback is needed)

The next model used three more (non-smoking) variables: Age_Enroll, gender, Height_CM.

As a result, a good additional predictor is whether a subject is > 56 yrs under certain conditions.

Remember also that the phenotype FEV1pp used to train the model has been adjusted for gender/age group/height/enth.

3 Covariates / grouping variables

Covariates used in both versions 0 and 1:

trait cov
FEV1pp_utah Age_Enroll, gender, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global
FEV1_utah Age_Enroll, Age_Enroll2, gender, Height_CM, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global
FVCpp_utah Age_Enroll, gender, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global
FVC_utah Age_Enroll, Age_Enroll2, gender, Height_CM, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global
FEV1_FVC_utah Age_Enroll, Age_Enroll2, gender, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global
log_pctEmph_Slicer Age_Enroll, gender, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global
TLCpp_race_adjusted Age_Enroll, gender, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global
finalGold_bin Age_Enroll, gender, SmokCigNow, ATS_PackYears, acs_global

Grouping variables used as random effects in version 1:

trait gr

    • Long segments are defined as those of length > 10kb.
    • The number of long segments: 37,194

Interaction models:

  • The only smoking variable used: SmokCigNow (binary)
    • The other variable ATS_PackYears is cont.
